opment of sheild and sword forms as it did in the west ).<br>
<br>
Both swords where traditionally worn togather by nobility ( aka Samuri ).<br>
<br>
The idea of a &quot;ninja Katana&quot; is laughable, by definition the katana has a sweep or curve to the blade the traditional weapon of the ninja, the ninjato, is a straight blade.  From smiths that I've spoken with it's actually harder to make a straight single edged weapon then a curved or swept blade.<br>
<br>
The True 2hander of fuedal Japan was a horse sword <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->   and it's not a katana of any sort.  Though it bears some similiarity.  Unfortunately the name eludes me at the time.<br>
<br>
All that not withstanding, Musashi  used what ever they hell he felt like to win duels, including boat oars <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :p --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":p"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
The weapon does not matter, the weilder does.  <br>
<br>
&quot;the purpose of the sword is to cut the enemy&quot;<br>
<br>
CheeChee<br>
<br>
